	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><persName role="author">MYER S. ISAACS</persName>&#44;</p>
			<p rend="align(right)">Attorney &#38; <sic>Counsellor</sic> at Law.</p>
			<p rend="align(right)">Notary Public&#44;</p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>243 BROADWAY&#44; ROOMS 9 AND 10</placeName>.</p>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName>&#44; <date>Aug 27th 1868</date></p>
				<p>My dear sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The receipt of your note and<lb/> enclosed communication reminds<lb/> me that I had neglected acknowl<lb/>edging receipt of notice of meeting<lb/> <persName>Mr Josephi<add>&#63;</add></persName> has gone to <placeName>Europe</placeName>&#44; it is<lb/> quite out of my power&#44; I regret to<lb/> say to be with you on <date>Monday</date>. I<lb/> can&#39;t speak for <persName>Mr. Sa<add>&#63;</add></persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">The article in the <hi rend="underline">Israelite</hi> is<lb/> scandalous &#8212; I had presumed an<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> reply which is in the<lb/> Messenger.  Yours of course is too late<lb/> this week &#40;rec&#39;d <date>Monday</date> at 10&#41;  but<lb/> it shall appear <hi rend="underline">entire</hi>&#44; I expect<lb/> next week with some remarks by<lb/> a &#8220;trustee.&#8221; While I feel that<lb/> this contemptible assault is in the<lb/> interest of men who fear their</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>&#8220;occupation will be gone&#8221; I <del>f</del><lb/> am as disgusted with our<lb/> orthodox brethren who are very<lb/> slow to appreciate the necessity<lb/> of Hebrew Education.  You find<lb/> us of the <hi rend="underline">Messenger</hi> working<add>&#63;</add> pretty<lb/> steadily with the <hi rend="underline">Occident</hi> on this<lb/> question&#44; but it is very&#44; very<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> work to get <hi rend="underline">money</hi> &#38;<lb/> <hi rend="underline">pupils</hi></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">You shall have 2 from <placeName>New York</placeName><lb/> &#40;2 pupils&#41; any others expected&#63;<lb/>  Please tell <persName>Mr Dropsie</persName> that I<lb/> have <sic>despatched</sic> his notes to our<lb/> leading congregations&#44; with<lb/> more misgivings than hopes.  We<lb/> must be unusually patient&#44;<lb/> &#38; persevere with the college<lb/> notwithstanding our limited</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>success with the public.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I feel personally that I ought<lb/> not to be a trustee because I lack<lb/> the time &#38; means to push the<lb/> work of money&#45;getting.  I&#39;ll make<lb/> another effort these holydays.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Don&#39;t be worried by the<lb/> barking of the <placeName>Cincinnati</placeName><lb/> hound.  Its&#39; characteristic.  He<lb/> is coming to <placeName>N. Y.</placeName> to dedicate<lb/> a Temple.  Perhaps he may<lb/> hear something to his advantage.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">With kind regards to <persName>Mr<lb/> Dropsie</persName> &#38; the Gentlemen of the<lb/> College</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I am</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Truly yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">M S Isaacs</persName></p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p><persName role="author">M S Isaacs</persName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><date>Aug. 27&#47;68</date></p>
